Domestic honeybees&nbsp;(<i>Apis mellifera</i>) help with pollinating crops worldwide, but they also compete with wild bees for nectar resources.&nbsp;   
When beekeepers introduced honeybees to a protected island, wild bees nearly vanished. Could removing the hives reverse the damage?&nbsp;

Since 2018, honeybees have feasted on wildflowers across a remote Italian island called Giannutri every spring. But for the last four years, Lorenzo Pasquali had the unusual task ofÂ shutting the honeybee hives down and watching wild bees as they scrambled to claim the flowers, racing for every drop of nectar in the absence of their domesticated rivals.

